y'(x) = \sqrt{-2y(x) + 28},\hspace{20 pt} y(-4)=-4
\int {1 \over \sqrt{28-2y} }\hspace{2 pt}\text{d}y = \int \text{d}x
-\sqrt{28-2y} = x + c
(28-2y) = (x+c)^2
y = -1/2x^2 - cx - c^2/2 + 14
c = {-2, 10}
\Rightarrow y = -1/2x^2 - 10x - 36
c=-2
c=10
y(x)=\frac{28-(x-2)^2}{2} = -\frac{x^2}{2} + 2x + 12.
y(x)
y=14
